774年","ABT 1754":"大约1754年","1839":"1839年","Ireland":"爱尔兰","lifeSummary":"当Gilbert De Nugent于大约1754年出生在爱尔兰时，他的父亲Sir Sir Fulke22岁，母亲Matilda De'L'aigle22岁。他至少有1个儿子。"},"hr":{"ABT 1754–":"oko 1754.–preminuo","1754–Male":"1754–preminuo","1774–Male":"1774–preminuo","1734–Male":"1734–preminuo","1734–Female":"1734–preminula","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"oko 1754.","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Irska"},"cs":{"ABT 1754–":"okolo 1754–Zesnulý","1754–Male":"1754–Zesnulý","1774–Male":"1774–Zesnulý","1734–Male":"1734–Zesnulý","1734–Female":"1734–Zesnulá","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"okolo 1754","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Irsko"},"da":{"ABT 1754–":"omkring 1754–Afdød","1754–Male":"1754–Afdød","1774–Male":"1774–Afdød","1734–Male":"1734–Afdød","1734–Female":"1734–Afdød","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"omkring 1754","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Irland"},"nl":{"ABT 1754–":"circa 1754–Overleden","1754–Male":"1754–Overleden","1774–Male":"1774–Overleden","1734–Male":"1734–Overleden","1734–Female":"1734–Overleden","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"circa 1754","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Ierland"},"en":{"ABT 1754–":"about 1754–Deceased","1754–Male":"1754–Deceased","1774–Male":"1774–Deceased","1734–Male":"1734–Deceased","1734–Female":"1734–Deceased","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"about 1754","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nugent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin), and northern French: habitational name from any of several places in northern France, such as Nogent-le-Sec and Nogent-sur-Eure (both in Eure), Nogent-le-Phaye, Nogent-le-Roi, and Nogent-le-Rotrou (all in Eure-et-Loir), Nogent-l'Abbesse (Marne), Nogent-l'Artaud (Aisne), and in particular Nogent-sur-Oise (Oise), named with Latin <i>Novientum</i>, apparently an altered form of a Gaulish name meaning ‘new settlement’.","Irish: in Ireland, this is generally the Norman name, but it was also adopted for <b>Mag Uinseanáin</b> (formerly Anglicized as <i>McGunshenan</i>, a variant of   Gilsenan  ), on the grounds of a fancied resemblance between <i>Uinseanán</i> and <i>Uinnseadún</i>.","History: The Anglo-Norman family of this name is descended from Fulke de Bellesme, lord of Nogent in Normandy, who was granted large estates around Winchester after the Conquest. His great-grandson was Hugh de Nugent (died 1213), who went to Ireland with Hugh de Lacy, and was granted lands in Bracklyn, County Westmeath. The family formed itself into a clan on the Irish model, of which the chief bore the hereditary title of <i>Uinsheadun</i> (Irish <i>Uinnseadún</i>), from their original seat at Winchester. They have been Earls of Westmeath since 1621. The name is now a common one in Ireland, and has been adopted there by some who have no connection with the clan."],"variants":[{"name":"Neugent","meanings":["English: variant of   Nugent  ."]},{"name":"Newgent","meanings":["Irish and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Nugent  ."]},{"name":"Nugen","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Nugent  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilsenan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colm.","Irish (Meath): shortened form of <b>MacGils(h)enan</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Seanáin</b> ‘son of the servant or devotee of Saint Senan’. Gilsenan has sometimes been Anglicized as   Gilson  , and a northern Irish variant <i>Mag Uinseanáin</i>, formerly Anglicized as <i>McGunshenan</i>, has now been replaced by   Nugent  .   Leonard   has also sometimes been adopted as equivalent."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355932,"age":44,"year":"1798","julianDay":2377767,"description":"Battle of Antrim.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1355933,"age":44,"year":"1798","julianDay":2377767,"description":"The Young Ireland rebellion of 1798 failed.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1355934,"age":85,"year":"1839","julianDay":2392741,"description":"The Night of the BIG WIND. In Killarney and its neighborhood there was a terrible hurricane. The town sustained much damage and many houses were shattered.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert De Nugent was born about 1754, in Ireland, his father, Sir Sir Fulke, was 22 and his mother, Matilda De'L'aigle, was 22. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1754–":"umbes 1754–Surnud","1754–Male":"1754–Surnud","1774–Male":"1774–Surnud","1734–Male":"1734–Surnud","1734–Female":"1734–Surnud","1734":"1734","1798":"1798","1754":"1754","1774":"1774","ABT 1754":"umbes 1754","1839":"1839","Ireland":"Iirimaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1754–":"noin 1754–Kuollut","1754–Male":"1754–Kuollut","1774–Male":"1774–Kuollut","1734–Male":"1734–Kuollut","1734–Female":"1734–Kuollut","1734":"1734","1798":"1798